context: Except for the <a0_0>five species<a0_0/> of monotremes (egg-laying mammals), all modern mammals give birth to <b4_0>live young<b4_0/>. Most mammals, including the six most species-rich orders, belong to <b5_0>the placental group<b5_0/>. The three largest orders in numbers, are first <a1_0><b6_0>Rodentia<b6_0/><a1_0/>: <b8_0>mice, rats, porcupines, beavers, capybaras, and other gnawing mammals<b8_0/>; then <b7_0>Chiroptera<b7_0/>: bats; and then Soricomorpha: shrews, moles and solenodons. The next three orders, depending on the biological classification scheme used, are the <a2_0>Primates<a2_0/> including the humans; the Cetartiodactyla including the whales and the even-toed hoofed mammals; and the <a3_0>Carnivora<a3_0/>, that is, cats, dogs, weasels, bears, seals, and their relatives.
